"section":10,"text":"The CSF (cerebrospinal fluid) results show very high protein, normal glucose, and a slightly elevated cell count.","dimension":1,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.03134,0.066828,0.094923,0.11176,0.11974,0.11889,0.114,0.097224,0.080856,0.065426,0.054934,0.044071],"unified_progress":[0.037609,0.07662,0.095373,0.1053,0.11046,0.10381,0.10212,0.092523,0.091332,0.074384,0.062084,0.048384]},{"section":11,"text":"High protein in CSF can indicate inflammation or infection, but since her glucose is normal, it's less likely to be a bacterial infection like meningitis, which often presents with high glucose.","dimension":5,"group":4,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.040503,0.058712,0.083392,0.096368,0.10489,0.1069,0.10957,0.099206,0.091808,0.084235,0.072411,0.052001],"unified_progress":[0.04097,0.066797,0.083462,0.092173,0.10081,0.10037,0.10435,0.099866,0.094331,0.091322,0.074165,0.051388]},{"section":12,"text":"The elevated cell count could mean there's some inflammation or maybe an immune response.","dimension":3,"group":6,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.039011,0.059968,0.08469,0.099125,0.10577,0.10669,0.10761,0.097596,0.088997,0.084129,0.069411,0.056997],"unified_progress":[0.040917,0.070165,0.087454,0.09718,0.10183,0.10071,0.10271,0.097495,0.09225,0.085226,0.07186,0.052195]},{"section":13,"text":"Putting this together, the high protein and elevated cells in the CSF make me think of something like Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome (GBS), which is an autoimmune condition where the body attacks the nerve endings in the brain and spinal cord.","dimension":3,"group":6,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.031476,0.053649,0.072574,0.086058,0.093775,0.098007,0.10158,0.10029,0.096711,0.09619,0.084228,0.085464],"unified_progress":[0.031669,0.059702,0.07821,0.090466,0.094501,0.10016,0.10012,0.098751,0.09572,0.091447,0.083419,0.075838]},{"section":14,"text":"It often follows an infection, like a chest cold, which she had three weeks ago.","dimension":0,"group":5,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.043971,0.076639,0.085361,0.085059,0.087258,0.089699,0.093402,0.094518,0.09467,0.093454,0.083079,0.072891],"unified_progress":[0.07156,0.095081,0.087673,0.084702,0.086616,0.089692,0.087161,0.091348,0.0859,0.081551,0.074369,0.064348]},{"section":15,"text":"GBS typically causes rapid progression of weakness and numbness, starting in the feet and moving up the legs, which matches her symptoms.","dimension":2,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.046457,0.06932,0.075165,0.08403,0.086768,0.092188,0.096093,0.099099,0.098356,0.090423,0.082979,0.079122],"unified_progress":[0.053211,0.073825,0.089321,0.088776,0.091101,0.099819,0.094577,0.095829,0.089356,0.085294,0.074746,0.064147]},{"section":16,"text":"The normal sensation testing might be because the damage is in the nerve roots, not the peripheral nerves.","dimension":1,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.046205,0.053424,0.072078,0.084692,0.093924,0.099761,0.10226,0.10227,0.098202,0.09063,0.083629,0.072928],"unified_progress":[0.045639,0.063435,0.079813,0.088585,0.09592,0.098383,0.09745,0.097153,0.097443,0.090774,0.079436,0.06597]},{"section":17,"text":"Another possibility is transverse myelitis, but that usually causes more severe and symmetric weakness, and the CSF might show other abnormalities like high cell count with predominant lymphocytes.","dimension":5,"group":4,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.025986,0.046035,0.068036,0.080351,0.091314,0.099824,0.10413,0.11006,0.1095,0.10313,0.092967,0.06867],"unified_progress":[0.029532,0.055645,0.074736,0.085725,0.095489,0.10114,0.10234,0.10472,0.10344,0.10313,0.084242,0.05986]},{"section":18,"text":"Since her cell count is slightly elevated and the protein is high, GBS seems more likely.","dimension":7,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.034703,0.048912,0.068339,0.079096,0.088086,0.092803,0.094027,0.095567,0.097016,0.096684,0.10048,0.10428],"unifi